<main class="container">
    <!-- Introduction Section -->
    <section id="introduction" class="content-section">
        <h2>Introduction</h2>

        <h3>Core Principles</h3>

        <p>StorPunk implements a complete decentralized ecosystem based on cypherpunk principles: privacy through cryptography, individual sovereignty, and resistance to centralized control. While built on a foundation of configurable data storage, the network aims to provide a comprehensive suite of tools for digital sovereignty.</p>

        <p>The system provides configurable data storage with user-defined expiration periods, creating censorship-resistant infrastructure that serves as the foundation for data storage, communication, and economic exchange tools.</p>

        <p><strong>System Features:</strong></p>
        <p>- Configurable data storage with user-defined expiration</p>
        <p>- Encrypted communication channels with IP masking capabilities</p>
        <p>- Decentralized native currency exchange at launch</p>
        <p>- Native non-blockchain token with market-based incentives</p>
        <p>- Fully decentralized architecture with no central points of control</p>
        <p>- Censorship-resistant design for unrestricted access</p>

        <h3>Privacy by Design</h3>

        <p>Unlike traditional cloud storage where corporations control your data and can be compelled to reveal it, StorPunk provides true data sovereignty through cryptographic privacy. Users maintain full control over their data lifecycle without relying on corporate promises or permission-based systems. Privacy is achieved through cryptography, not through data expiration.</p>

        <p>In today's changing political climate, where free speech faces increasing challenges, proactive data protection becomes essential. StorPunk enables users to maintain control of their information regardless of external pressures.</p>

        <h3>Sustainable Economics</h3>

        <p>Centralized data storage creates vulnerability to complete data loss from infrastructure failures. Permanent decentralized storage networks face economic challenges from the ongoing cost of maintaining historical data indefinitely. StorPunk addresses both issues: distributed architecture prevents single points of failure, while temporary storage ensures economic sustainability by limiting data maintenance to defined periods.</p>

        <p>The temporary data approach eliminates network bloat and ensures users always pay market rates for storage. Clients set expiration dates that match their actual needs, and nodes price storage accordingly. This eliminates the risk of accumulating outdated information while ensuring costs remain transparent and market-based, preventing cascade collapse scenarios.</p>

        <h3>DAO Governance</h3>

        <p>The project uses a multi-phase token sale where $PUNK-DAO tokens are sold at <strong>1:1</strong> with USDT. These tokens provide governance rights and can be claimed for native $PUNK tokens with tier-based multipliers. After claiming, tokens become <span class="highlight highlight-term">soulbound</span> (non-transferable) while retaining governance rights.</p>


        <p>Development follows conservative treasury management with community voting via Snapshot.org. The Community Development Fund ensures ongoing ecosystem development and governance long after initial phases conclude.</p>

        <h3>Complete Ecosystem Vision</h3>

        <p>While data storage provides the foundational layer, StorPunk aims to create a complete ecosystem for digital sovereignty:</p>

        <p>- <strong>Financial Infrastructure</strong>: A decentralized exchange supporting fiat and cryptocurrency trading without intermediaries</p>
        <p>- <strong>Trading Platform</strong>: A general marketplace for goods and services operating without central authorities</p>
        <p>- <strong>Communication Tools</strong>: Censorship-resistant social media and information exchange capabilities</p>
        <p>- <strong>Economic Foundation</strong>: A native token with transaction capacity designed to rival traditional systems</p>

        <h3>Network Features</h3>

        <h4>Launch Features</h4>

        <div class="features">
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Configurable Data Storage Network</h3>
                <p>A decentralized storage network supporting user-defined data retention periods. The client interface is designed to support storing data to both StorPunk and Autonomi networks, providing flexibility options.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Native Network Token ($PUNK)</h3>
                <p>A fixed-supply native token intended for network transactions and operations. Value maintenance is designed through direct economic activity rather than inflationary mechanisms.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Decentralized Currency Exchange</h3>
                <p>A decentralized exchange system planned to operate on the StorPunk network. Designed to enable trading between $PUNK tokens, fiat currencies, and selected cryptocurrencies without intermediaries.</p>
        </div>


        <h4>Post-Launch Features</h4>

        <div class="features">
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Network Search</h3>
                <p>Planned network-wide indexing and search functionality for public data. This collaborative system between nodes and clients is designed to enable efficient discovery while maintaining privacy.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Social Media Communications</h3>
                <p>Client-side social media functionality leveraging the network's privacy-preserving architecture. Designed to enable secure, censorship-resistant communication independent of traditional platforms.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Decentralized Trading Platform</h3>
                <p>A general trading platform for goods and services planned for the StorPunk network. Intended to create a marketplace for exchange without central authorities.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-card">
                <h3>Network Hops</h3>
                <p>Anonymous usage capabilities through network hops similar to Tor's onion routing. Designed to enhance privacy by masking user IP addresses and locations.</p>
        </div>

    </section>
<content>
    <!-- Decentralized Autonomous Organization (DAO) Section -->
    <section id="dao" class="content-section">
        <h2>Decentralized Autonomous Organization (DAO)</h2>

        <p>The StorPunk DAO implements decentralized governance over the network's development and treasury. Operating without central authority, it enables token holders to make collective decisions about technical direction and resource allocation. The governance system maintains transparency and operates through cryptographically verified voting.</p>

        <h3>$PUNK-DAO Token</h3>

        <p>The $PUNK-DAO token (ERC-20) serves two primary purposes:</p>

        <p>- <strong>Fundraising:</strong> Sold in tiers to raise capital for sustainable, long-term development.</p>
        <p>- <strong>Permanent Governance:</strong> Token holders vote on key decisions via Snapshot.org, maintaining their voice even after claiming $PUNK tokens.</p>

        <h3>Tiered Sale Structure</h3>

        <p>$PUNK-DAO tokens are sold at a <strong>1:1</strong> ratio with USDT. The tier in which you purchase determines your $PUNK network token multiplier at launch:</p>


        <div class="code-block">
            <div class="block-header">Token Sale Tiers & Multipliers</div>
            <ul>
                <li>Tier 1: 0-250,000 USDT → 1 USDT = 1 $PUNK-DAO, with <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">16x</span> $PUNK multiplier at launch</li>
                <li>Tier 2: 250,001-700,000 USDT → 1 USDT = 1 $PUNK-DAO, with <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">8x</span> $PUNK multiplier at launch</li>
                <li>Tier 3: 700,001-1,350,000 USDT → 1 USDT = 1 $PUNK-DAO, with <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">4x</span> $PUNK multiplier at launch</li>
                <li>Tier 4: 1,350,001-2,350,000+ USDT → 1 USDT = 1 $PUNK-DAO, with <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">2x</span> $PUNK multiplier at launch</li>
        </div>


        <h3>Holding Mechanism</h3>

        <p>The system includes multiplier incentives for token retention. At network launch:</p>

        <p>- <strong>Original purchasers</strong> who never transferred their $PUNK-DAO tokens receive an additional <strong>2x multiplier</strong> on their $PUNK tokens. This doubles the tier multiplier - for example, a Tier 1 buyer (<span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">16x</span>) who never transfers their tokens would receive a <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">32x</span> multiplier (<span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">16x</span> × <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">2x</span>).</p>
        <p>- <strong>Secondary buyers</strong> only receive the base tier multiplier without the additional <span class="highlight highlight-multiplier">2x</span></p>

        <p>- Claiming happens on Ethereum—the contract verifies your holding history automatically</p>

        <h3>Soulbound Governance</h3>

        <p>After claiming your $PUNK tokens, your $PUNK-DAO tokens become <span class="highlight highlight-term">soulbound</span> (non-transferable):</p>


        <p>1. You call the claim function on Ethereum, providing your StorPunk address</p>
        <p>2. Your $PUNK-DAO tokens become permanently locked to your wallet</p>
        <p>3. A bridge service detects your claim and mints $PUNK on StorPunk</p>
        <p>4. You keep full voting rights forever—governance stays on Ethereum</p>

        <p><strong>Purpose of soulbound mechanism:</strong> This creates separation between governance rights and token speculation. Only unclaimed tokens trade on markets, maintaining governance among participants with demonstrated commitment to the network's principles and development.</p>


        <h3>Sustainable Funding Model</h3>

        <div class="code-block">
            <div class="block-header">4-Phase Development Timeline</div>
            <ul>
                <li>DAO launches with full operations at end of Phase 0</li>
                <li>Treasury management begins before development funding</li>
                <li>Target: Sustainable runway through multiple development phases</li>
                <li>Each tier funds a specific development phase</li>
                <li>Native P2P exchange with multisig trade security prioritized (Phase 3)</li>
                <li>New tiers start only when needed</li>
                <li>Limited sale windows</li>
                <li>Unsold tokens allocated 60/40 to Founder/Developer Pool and Community Development Fund</li>
        </div>


        <h3>Governance Platform</h3>

        <p><strong>Vote on proposals at snapshot.org (gasless voting):</strong></p>
        <p>- Treasury management decisions</p>
        <p>- Tier initiation timing</p>
        <p>- Development priorities (P2P exchange with multisig trade security in Phase 3)</p>
        <p>- Emergency actions if needed</p>
        <p>- Network upgrade approvals</p>
        <p>- Connect wallet → Read proposals → Vote for free</p>

        <h3>Current Status</h3>

        <div class="code-block">
            <div class="block-header">Current DAO Status</div>
            <ul>
                <li>In development</li>
                <li>Launching at end of Phase 0 with initial operations</li>
                <li>Unsold tokens allocated 60/40 to developers and Community Development Fund</li>
                <li>Visit the <a href="#join-us">Join Us</a> section to connect with our community</li>
        </div>


        <p>$PUNK-DAO token acquisition provides permanent governance rights that remain active even after claiming native tokens. This structure maintains long-term accountability to token holders while allowing the network to evolve. The development prioritizes P2P exchange with multisig security in Phase 3, enabling censorship-resistant trade between participants without intermediaries or permission requirements. This includes direct peer-to-peer exchanges with fiat currency.</p>

        <h3>Community Development Fund</h3>

        <p>A portion of unsold tokens from each tier (<strong>40%</strong>) is allocated to the Community Development Fund:</p>


        <p>- <strong>Long-term Support:</strong> Funds open-source development and community initiatives for years or decades after the main development phases are complete.</p>
        <p>- <strong>Developer Incentives:</strong> Rewards community contributors who enhance the StorPunk ecosystem.</p>
        <p>- <strong>Minimum Requirement:</strong> Community developers need to hold at least <strong>100</strong> $PUNK-DAO tokens to be eligible for fund grants.</p>

        <p>- <strong>Community Governance:</strong> Fund allocation decisions made through the same DAO voting mechanisms.</p>

        <p>StorPunk implements temporary data storage based on cypherpunk principles of individual sovereignty and censorship resistance. The system architecture protects user privacy through cryptography rather than policy. The Community Development Fund provides ongoing resources for infrastructure enhancement and adaptation to evolving threats against digital freedom, with governance remaining in the hands of token holders indefinitely.</p>
    </section>
</content>
<content>
    <!-- Cypherpunk Foundations: StorPunk's Philosophical and Technical Principles Section -->
    <section id="foundations" class="content-section">
        <h2>Cypherpunk Foundations: StorPunk's Philosophical and Technical Principles</h2>

        <p>StorPunk implements decentralized infrastructure based on cypherpunk principles: privacy through cryptography, individual sovereignty, and resistance to centralized control. This document outlines the philosophical foundations and technical approach that guide StorPunk's development.</p>

        <h3>FOUNDATIONAL PRINCIPLES</h3>

        <h4>1. Cypherpunk Philosophy</h4>

        <p><strong>"Privacy is necessary for an open society in the electronic age."</strong> — The Cypherpunk Manifesto</p>


        <p>StorPunk embodies core cypherpunk principles: strong cryptography, peer-to-peer architecture, voluntary association, and resistance to censorship. The project builds systems designed to protect individual sovereignty against both corporate surveillance and state control.</p>

        <p>By implementing cryptographic privacy for data storage and communication, StorPunk aims to provide users with control over their digital existence. Privacy is achieved through cryptography, not through data expiration mechanisms.</p>

        <p>This approach represents a commitment to decentralization—both technical architecture and philosophical opposition to concentrated control, whether corporate or governmental.</p>

        <h4>2. Resistance to Censorship</h4>

        <p><strong>In an era of expanding digital control, censorship-resistant infrastructure serves essential functions.</strong></p>


        <p>As digital environments face increasing regulation and surveillance, the need for infrastructure that resists centralized control grows more apparent. StorPunk creates systems designed to remain operational across varying regulatory conditions.</p>

        <p>The architecture resists content filtering, metadata collection, and centralized control points. This technical approach supports access to information and communication regardless of external pressures or platform policies.</p>

        <p>Beyond privacy protection, the network supports epistemic freedom—the ability to think, communicate, and access information without surveillance or censorship constraints.</p>

        <h4>3. Privacy Through Architecture</h4>

        <p><strong>In digital systems, privacy should be fundamental to the architecture, not an optional feature.</strong></p>


        <p>StorPunk implements privacy at the architectural level through cryptographic protections. In digital environments, control over data determines sovereignty over that data. When data becomes accessible to others without consent, it can be used against individual interests.</p>

        <p>The network aims to provide tools for digital sovereignty, enabling users to maintain control over their data and transactions. This approach reduces the need to move data between networks and risk exposure through multiple points of vulnerability.</p>

        <p>As Eric Hughes wrote in the Cypherpunk Manifesto, "For privacy to be widespread it must be part of a social contract. People must come and together deploy these systems for the common good." StorPunk represents this collective deployment approach.</p>

        <h3>TECHNICAL IMPLEMENTATION</h3>

        <h4>4. User Sovereignty and Self-Custody</h4>

        <p><strong>Digital sovereignty requires control over both data and economic assets.</strong></p>


        <p>StorPunk implements a self-custody model where users maintain control of their data, metadata, encryption keys, and tokens. No third party—including StorPunk developers—can access user information or assets without explicit permission.</p>

        <p>The focus on usable implementation means cryptographic protections are designed to be accessible to regular users, not just technical experts. The architecture aims to make privacy and censorship resistance available through practical interfaces.</p>

        <p>The cypherpunk approach emphasizes working code that enables individuals to exercise digital rights across various environmental conditions.</p>

        <h4>5. Engineering for Resilience</h4>

        <p><strong>Sustainable systems require engineering that remains viable under real-world conditions.</strong></p>


        <p>StorPunk's architecture prioritizes long-term operation through several technical choices:</p>

        <p>- <strong>Rust implementation</strong> for memory safety and performance</p>
        <p>- <strong>Temporary storage model</strong> that addresses data accumulation and hardware requirements</p>
        <p>- <strong>Minimal transaction fees</strong> that support network operations without significant user cost</p>
        <p>- <strong>Peer-to-peer design</strong> that avoids single points of failure</p>

        <p>The temporary storage approach provides economic and operational benefits. By automatically removing expired data, the network avoids the storage accumulation that challenges permanent storage systems.</p>

        <p>This practical engineering focus aims to ensure that censorship-resistant infrastructure remains available and sustainable regardless of external conditions.</p>

        <h3>ECONOMIC MODEL</h3>

        <h4>6. Private Economic Exchange</h4>

        <p><strong>Freedom requires both private communication and economic exchange capabilities.</strong></p>


        <p>StorPunk integrates native exchange capabilities, enabling peer-to-peer value transfer designed to resist financial surveillance and third-party interference. This creates economic infrastructure where transactions can remain private and accessible across geographic and political boundaries.</p>

        <p>The native token uses <strong>minimal transaction fees</strong> to deter network manipulation while maintaining low costs.</p>


        <p>By enabling direct exchanges between individuals without intermediaries, StorPunk supports economic interactions based on voluntary agreement rather than permission requirements.</p>

        <p>This approach implements principles of cryptographic consent and reputation-based interaction systems.</p>

        <h4>7. Voluntary Economic Model</h4>

        <p><strong>Genuine markets depend on voluntary exchange without coercion.</strong></p>


        <p>StorPunk implements a direct market model where node operators receive compensation from storage fees, eliminating centrally-issued token rewards. This creates a voluntary network where participants interact through mutual agreement.</p>

        <p>The economic design relies on direct service payments, establishing a model where token value corresponds to actual network usage. Users pay for the storage they need, for the duration they require it, while operators provide service at freely determined prices.</p>

        <p>This extends cypherpunk principles into economics, creating interaction based on cryptographic proof and consent rather than intermediation.</p>

        <h3>COMPLETE ECOSYSTEM VISION</h3>

        <p>While data storage provides the foundational layer, StorPunk aims to create a complete ecosystem for digital sovereignty:</p>

        <p>- <strong>Financial Infrastructure</strong>: Exchange capabilities supporting various asset types</p>
        <p>- <strong>Trading Platform</strong>: Marketplace for goods and services without central authorities</p>
        <p>- <strong>Communication Tools</strong>: Censorship-resistant information exchange</p>
        <p>- <strong>Economic Foundation</strong>: Native token with transaction capacity</p>

        <h3>STRATEGIC APPROACH</h3>

        <p>John Gilmore, a cypherpunk founder, observed the race between technology deployment and regulatory development. StorPunk's development follows this imperative—building and deploying privacy technology to establish operational infrastructure.</p>

        <p>The project represents practical implementation of cypherpunk principles, creating infrastructure that enables:</p>
        <p>- Private economic transactions resistant to surveillance</p>
        <p>- Communication channels that support free inquiry</p>
        <p>- Decentralized systems without central control points</p>
        <p>- Voluntary association based on cryptographic consent</p>

        <p>As digital environments face increasing challenges to privacy and freedom, StorPunk provides tools designed to maintain digital sovereignty.</p>

        <h3>Cypherpunk Resources</h3>

        <p>- <a href="https://www.activism.net/cypherpunk/manifesto.html">The Cypherpunk Manifesto</a> - Eric Hughes' 1993 text on privacy and cryptography</p>
        <p>- <a href="https://nakamotoinstitute.org/crypto-anarchist-manifesto/">The Crypto Anarchist Manifesto</a> - Timothy May's 1988 vision of cryptography's role</p>
        <p>- <a href="https://www.eff.org/cyberspace-independence">A Declaration of the Independence of Cyberspace</a> - John Perry Barlow's statement on digital sovereignty</p>
        <p>- <a href="https://www.cypherpunks.to/faq/cyphernomicon/cyphernomicon.txt">Cyphernomicon</a> - Timothy May's cypherpunk exploration</p>

        <p>StorPunk continues this tradition of cypherpunk innovation—using cryptography, decentralization, and peer-to-peer architecture to support fundamental digital freedoms. Privacy, voluntary exchange, and resistance to censorship represent essential components of open digital societies.</p>
    </section>
</content>
